s we explain, enshrine, and, above all, evade death in contemporary culture. Some poems are personal – a parent tries to explain to a child why a grandfather is in hospital, or stages a funeral for a child's imaginary friend – while others comment on how death figures in the news, on TV, and in social media. Some poems ask if there is any place left for poets in our rituals of memory and commemoration. A few examine the apocalyptic language of climate change. Others poke fun at the death-defying claims of posthumanism. A thoughtful and irreverent collection about serious concerns, The Art of Dying begins and ends with the fact of death, and strips away our euphemisms about it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCanadian poetryy21st century. 0aCanadian poetry. 7aPOETRY / Canadian.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311127363108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018z978311127598740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780773552722?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773552722423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773552722/original  a978-3-11-127363-1  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-127598-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles